<br>
First off, I do think it is sad, and extremely bad in appearance for religions, to see what others do in the name of religion. So many people do terrible things in the name of God and call it religion, call themselves whatever they may, believe they are saved because they did something they see as spiritually noble. In regards to 9/11, I remember thinking about how religious types must have looked to those who didn't believe in God. I remember thinking that for me, who believes in God, thinking &quot;How could someone believe that God would want this?&quot; and yet for someone who doesn't believe in God, I'm sure that the anger ran even deeper. For me, I do have one thing in common with those terrorists... I believe in that higher power, that God that they believe they did this for. I believe that they are getting their just rewards for what they did and I don't think it is paradise for them. I believe Hell was created for people like that. Anyway, I digress... those who don't maintain a belief in God or a higher power, afterlife, I'm sure it is just down right reprehensible to think that someone did something like that for absolutely NOTHING... <br>
<br>
It's interesting to me that as an LDS member, I can look at the Mountain Meadows Massacre and see the absolute disgrace it was. I can see how it was needless for those people to die and that it never should have happened. Yet, unlike the terrorists of 9/11, I can imagine what the early Mormon's were most likely feeling. I can see how they would be afraid, untrusting and how they attacked wrongfully because they weren't sure if these people in the wagon train were really there to exterminate them. It was still wrong. I don't know. I don't know enough about that event but even if they were afraid, striking as they did was wrong (hmmm... seems similar  to the &quot;pre-emptive strike&quot; that looks to be inevitable in Iraq) and yet at the same time, to sit back and see if they are going to kill you first doesn't provide much security for your family. Maybe it is because I am a member of the same church that I can find &quot;reasons&quot; or justifications for why that happened. Yet I can't even begin to justify why someone would fly a plane into a building. <br>
<br>
In reality, Christian religions, if they truly follow the teachings of Jesus Christ, would not look for fights, be aggressors in a murder, etc... Christ, whether you believe he was divine or not, taught to turn the other cheek and because Christian religions believe that he was the Messiah and that he was not an ordinary man, base their belief systems on his teaching and example. <br>
<br>
I guess I don't really know where I was going with this... It's getting too late to remember what my point was even going to be.  But, totally OT, I would really like to express a gripe I have... does it bother anyone but me that our government is looking for Americans to blame for 9/11? They are trying to pin down who was responsible... I'll tell ya who, the terrorists! They are the ones who chose to do what they did and yet we Americans are constantly trying to find other people to blame! I'm sorry but that is what my 3 yr old does. The terrorists are to blame... no one else. Sure, there were cracks in our Intelligence but you know, they are not mind readers, the last time I checked. Just had to add that since I didn't have anywhere else to post it! Been stewing over it for a couple weeks and it feels great to finally say it somewhere! Sorry!<br>
<br>
