<br>
At one point I said:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think the guidance of the Spirit can aid us, though I do not believe it is supposed to replace reason, it supplements it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And dag said somewhere after that, possibly misinterpreting what I meant:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>i too see faith as supplementation<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I actually do not think of faith and the Spirit as interchangeable, they are two different things.<br>
<br>
Faith, to me, is a belief in something this is true but which can't be seen or proved, at least at the current time.<br>
<br>
The Spirit is like our conscience.  It <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>is not supposed to replace reason.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  It guides it, supplements it.  It can also supplement our faith and make it stronger, but faith and the Spirit are not the same thing.<br>
<br>
For instance, if a person were theorizing about something, the Spirit might help lead them toward the correct path to pursue to find the answer and help the person recognize the answer when it is found.<br>
<br>
Faith, would be like believing the Word of Wisdom (dietary guide for LDS) and following it even though you didn't understand the specifics of why it was healthier. Many people did not use tobacco because they had faith that the Word of Wisdom was true.  Nowadays, we know a whole lot about why smoking and chewing it is unhealthy, so knowledge has replaced faith in that way.  We are to have Faith until that day when we have a sure knowledge.<br>
<br>
The whole purpose of life is to come here and be able to learn for ourselves what is good and what is not  and then act accordingly (agency) and reap the consequences good and bad.<br>
<br>
For that reason, true religion should not replace reason and logic, to the contrary it should demand it's use IMO.  We strive to be above doing things because of outside forces,  to move beyond doing things simply because &quot;it's the norm&quot; (even if the right choice is &quot;the norm&quot; that shouldn't be why we choose it), and instead  do things because that is inherently who we are, because it is our will to do them.<br>
<br>
God's will is perfect, and He would like us to develop ours to be like His and does try to guide us that way, but does not force us, he couldn't, it wouldn't work that way any more than a pianist could transfer his ability into another person.<br>
<br>
But true religion will also include things of a spiritual nature.  The Spirit and knowledge will never contradict each other, Truth is Truth.    If there is an apparent contradiction either a person is listening to their &quot;comfort zone&quot; and crediting it to the Spirit or else they are missing something in their secular search for knowledge, KWIM?<br>
<br>
